In Unreal Engine 5, when working with the Gameplay Ability System (GAS), OverlapMultiByObjectType can be a useful function to detect overlapping Actors based on their collision object type. In order to use this function in a ground Actor, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure that GAS is enabled in your UE5 project. Check the project settings, under Plugins, and enable the Gameplay Ability System if it is not yet enabled.

2. Open your ground Actor Blueprint or C++ class, where you want to implement the OverlapMultiByObjectType.

3. Create a function or event that will handle the overlap check. For example, you could name it "Check Overlapping Actors".

4. To use OverlapMultiByObjectType, you will need a Start location and a QueryParams.

```cpp
FVector StartLocation = GetActorLocation(); // or any custom location
FCollisionQueryParams QueryParams;
QueryParams.AddIgnoredActor(this); // Ignore the ground actor itself in the query
```

5. Define the Object Types you want to detect. For example, you can use 'WorldDynamic' and 'Pawn' object types.

```cpp
FCollisionObjectQueryParams ObjectTypes;
ObjectTypes.AddObjectTypesToQuery(ECC_WorldDynamic);
ObjectTypes.AddObjectTypesToQuery(ECC_Pawn);
```

6. In Blueprint or C++, call OverlapMultiByObjectType function.

```cpp
TArray<FOverlapResult> OverlappingActors;
GetWorld()->OverlapMultiByObjectType(OverlappingActors, StartLocation, FQuat::Identity, ObjectTypes, FCollisionShape::MakeSphere(200.0f), QueryParams);
```

7. Now you have an array of FOverlapResult objects called "OverlappingActors". Loop through these results and use the GetActor() function to access the actual Actors that are overlapping.

```cpp
for (FOverlapResult& Result : OverlappingActors)
{
    AActor* OverlappingActor = Result.GetActor();
    // Your custom logic with the overlapping actors
}
```

8. Call your "Check Overlapping Actors" function whenever required, for example, in Event BeginPlay or periodically with a timer.

Repeat these steps for multiple ground actors or any other Actors in which you want to detect overlaps using OverlapMultiByObjectType.

Remember that this is just one approach, and depending on your project requirements, you might need to adjust or optimize the logic.

Sure! Here's an example of how you might create `FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle` for multiple actors using C++ code in Unreal Engine.

Let's assume that you have an array of `AActor*` called `TargetActors` from which you want to create target data.

```cpp
#include "GameplayAbilitySpec.h"

// Your function that creates target data for multiple actors
FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle CreateTargetDataForMultipleActors(const TArray<AActor*>& TargetActors)
{
    FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle TargetDataHandle;

    // Loop through the actor array and create target data for each actor
    for (AActor* TargetActor : TargetActors)
    {
        if (!TargetActor) // Skip if the actor pointer is null
            continue;

        // Create an instance of FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit and set hit result
        TSharedPtr<FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit> TargetData = MakeShareable(new FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit());
        TargetData->SetHitResult(FHitResult(TargetActor));

        // Add target data to the handle
        TargetDataHandle.Add(TargetData);
    }

    return TargetDataHandle;
}
```

You can then call this function and pass the `TargetActors` array to create target data for those actors:

```cpp
TArray<AActor*> TargetActors;
// Fill TargetActors array with the actors you want to create target data for

FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle TargetDataHandle = CreateTargetDataForMultipleActors(TargetActors);

// Pass the TargetDataHandle to your ability or other functions that require target data
```

This example demonstrates how to create an `FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle` from an array of actors using C++ code in Unreal Engine with the Gameplay Ability System. Make sure to adjust the code based on your specific project requirements.

Apologies for the confusion. It seems I used the wrong type for `TargetData`. You should create an instance of `FGameplayAbilityTargetData` instead of `TSharedPtr<FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit, ESPMode::ThreadSafe>`.

Here's the corrected code:

```cpp
#include "GameplayAbilitySpec.h"

// Your function that creates target data for multiple actors
FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle CreateTargetDataForMultipleActors(const TArray<AActor*>& TargetActors)
{
    FGameplayAbilityTargetDataHandle TargetDataHandle;

    // Loop through the actor array and create target data for each actor
    for (AActor* TargetActor : TargetActors)
    {
        if (!TargetActor) // Skip if the actor pointer is null
            continue;

        // Create an instance of FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit and set hit result
        FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit TargetData;
        TargetData.SetHitResult(FHitResult(TargetActor));

        // Create a TSharedPtr for the TargetData
        TSharedPtr<FGameplayAbilityTargetData> TargetDataPtr = MakeShareable(new FGameplayAbilityTargetData_SingleTargetHit(TargetData));

        // Add target data to the handle
        TargetDataHandle.Add(TargetDataPtr);
    }

    return TargetDataHandle;
}
```

This should resolve the error you mentioned. Now, you can call this function and pass the `TargetActors` array to create target data for those actors without encountering the conversion issue.

The best way to send the center of the AOE to an ability in Unreal Engine is to include it as part of the target data when activating the ability. This ensures that the ability has all the information it needs to execute, including the center of AOE and the list of targets within the AOE.

Here's an approach on how to do this:

1. Create a custom class that inherits from `FGameplayAbilityTargetData`, for example `FGameplayAbilityTargetData_AOECenter`.

2. In your custom target data class, include an FVector variable to represent the center of the AOE.

```cpp
UPROPERTY(BlueprintReadOnly, Category = "Gameplay Ability Target Data")
FVector AOECenter;
```

3. Create a constructor and a function to initialize the custom target data based on the AOE center location:

```cpp
FGameplayAbilityTargetData_AOECenter()
    : AOECenter(FVector::ZeroVector) {}

void SetAOECenter(const FVector& Center)
{
     AOECenter = Center;
}
```

4. When you create target data for your ability (mouse click, overlap, etc.), also create an instance of your custom target data class and set the AOE center location.

```cpp
FGameplayAbilityTargetData_AOECenter AOETargetData;
AOETargetData.SetAOECenter(AOECenter);
TSharedPtr<FGameplayAbilityTargetData> AOETargetDataPtr = MakeShareable(new FGameplayAbilityTargetData_AOECenter(AOETargetData));
TargetDataHandle.Add(AOETargetDataPtr);
```

5. Add the other target actors to your target data handle as usual.

6. Activate your ability using the target data handle.

7. In your ability, retrieve the custom target data (AOE center information) from the target data handle.

```cpp
const FGameplayAbilityTargetData_AOECenter* AOETargetData = TargetDataHandle.Get(0)->GetAOETargetData();
if (AOETargetData)
{
    FVector AOECenter = AOETargetData->AOECenter;
    // Your logic to move the character based on AOE center location
}
```

This will allow you to access the AOE center location in your ability and perform any required actions such as moving the character to a specific distance away from the AOE center.

By following this method, you can pass the center position of a clicked location in the target list and move your character based on that information. Keep in mind that you may need to make small adjustments to this method depending on your specific project requirements.

